<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="manso" data-post="3" data-topic="450759">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/e99b99/48.png" class="avatar"> manso:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>I see that there is a member method called <code>getSupplyVoltage()</code> I’m assuming that I can just plug that in here</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>This would not work with a CANcoder. Rather, this is a way to get the absolute position of an analog encoder connected to ANALOG IN and using the AnalogInput class. An analog encoder reports a proportion of the voltage from the 5 V rail based on its absolute position, so dividing the reported voltage by the measured 5 V rail voltage gives the absolute position. This is essentially what the WPILib AnalogEncoder class does for you.</p>
<p>However, the CANcoder is NOT an analog encoder; it is a magnetic encoder that communicates over the <span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> bus. The CANcoder looks at the magnetic field generated by the magnet to determine its orientation, which is the absolute position. The CANcoder <code>getSupplyVoltage()</code> simply returns the voltage supplied to the CANcoder by the battery, which is typically around 12 V. The <strong>only</strong> way to get its absolute position within [-0.5, 0.5) or [0, 1) is <code>getAbsolutePosition()</code>.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2024-01-18T21:12:29.326Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":5,"reads":62,"readers_count":61,"score":52.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":450759,"topic_slug":"how-to-get-radians-voltage-from-ctre-cancoder","display_username":"Benjamin Hall","primary_group_name":"CTRE","flair_name":"CTRE","flair_url":"/uploads/default/original/3X/1/b/1bd2b430e1bb6427d1c6504ff6abcd31de851a6d.png","flair_bg_color":"","flair_color":"","flair_group_id":57,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":4}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48146,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics"},"post_url":"/t/how-to-get-radians-voltage-from-ctre-cancoder/450759/4","custom_user_title":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics","reactions":[{"id":"point_up","type":"emoji","count":2},{"id":"+1","type":"emoji","count":1},{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":4,"current_use